▸ video_prompt（English only — motion description for Kling/Seedance video AI）
  - Core principle: describe EVERY element's motion individually and specifically. Keyword lists are forbidden.
    Generic phrases like "fluid motion" or "dynamic atmosphere" add nothing — describe the actual physics.
  - Required motion layers (all applicable layers must be present):
    A. Camera: exact movement type matching camera_type + speed qualifier
       static → "locked-off with organic micro-stabilization, imperceptible ±0.3px breathing drift"
       push   → "slow cinematic dolly-push at 0.2x speed, closing distance by ~30% over shot duration"
       pan    → "smooth leftward pan at 15°/sec, horizon line held steady throughout"
    B. Subject primary motion: BEGIN with a one-line initial state declaration for EACH character, then describe motion
       Initial state (mandatory before any motion): "[character name] [posture] [frame position], [body orientation], [left hand doing X], [right hand doing Y]"
       ✅ "Hunter stands mid-ground-right, body ¾ turned toward wolf, left hand resting on grandmother's shoulder, right hand holding open scissors at waist — then right arm extends forward 15cm over 1.2 seconds..."
       ❌ Starting motion description without declaring where/how each character starts → AI fabricates starting state
       — which body part moves, direction, arc/trajectory, speed, acceleration curve (ease-in/ease-out)
       — secondary body responses: clothing/hair reacting to primary motion with physics delay
    C. Subject micro-motion (always required, even for static poses):
       — breathing rhythm (visible chest/shoulder rise: amplitude, rate)
       — involuntary tremors, muscle tension pulses, eye movement or blinking
       — gravity effects: weight pressing into surface, fabric settling
    D. Scene dynamic elements: each environmental element gets its own motion clause
       — particles (dust/smoke/embers/petals): origin, drift direction, density change, fall rate
       — fabric/foliage: wind effect, amplitude in degrees, frequency
       — liquids/fire: flow direction, flicker rhythm, intensity change
    E. Lighting dynamics (if any): how light changes within the shot duration
       — intensity ramp (brightening/dimming), color temperature shift, shadow edge migration
    F. Temporal arc: how the shot's emotional energy evolves from start to finish
  - Example (locked-off, wounded character in wasteland):
    "Locked-off camera with subtle organic stabilization, imperceptible breathing drift of ±0.5px;
    Chen Fan lies on his side foreground-center — upper body slowly coils tighter over the shot duration,
    arms drawing inward incrementally as pain surges, each breath producing 4-6mm shoulder-rise followed
    by a longer deflation; fingers alternately clench (knuckles blanching) and release in 3-second
    irregular cycles; a single dried grass stalk 15cm left of his torso sways 8° in response to his
    exhaled breath, recovering over 1.2 seconds with slight overshoot oscillation; fractured clay ground
    surface shows fine grit particles dislodged by his body tremors rolling 2-3cm into nearby crevices;
    overcast sky layer holds motionless, amplifying time-suspension; cold grey diffuse top-light dims
    ~15% over shot duration, shadows deepening without directional shift; emotional arc progresses from
    stunned endurance at frame-open to teetering-on-edge despair at frame-close, tension accumulating
    without release"

